figure_1.title: Fig 1. Example stimuli from Experiment 3.
figure_1.caption: We are unable to share examples of the stimuli from Experiments 1 and 2 because of copyright issues.

figure_2.title: Fig 2. Experiments 1–3: Boxplots depicting ratings of human infants and puppy dogs, as a function of whether their eyes were visible or concealed.
figure_2.caption: The boxplots describe data combined across all three experiments. Boxes indicate interquartile ranges. Bold horizontal lines indicate medians. Red dots indicated means. Black dots indicate outliers.

figure_3.title: Fig 3. Example stimuli from Experiment 5.
figure_3.caption: We are unable to share examples of the stimuli from Experiment 4 because of copyright issues.

figure_4.title: Fig 4. Experiments 4 and 5: Boxplots depicting ratings of human infants and puppy dogs, as a function of whether their eye gaze was direct or averted in Experiments 4 to 5.
figure_4.caption: The boxplots describe data combined across both experiments. Boxes indicate interquartile ranges. Bold horizontal lines indicate medians. Red dots indicated means. Black dots indicate outliers.

There was also evidence—which emerged somewhat less consistently across studies—that when perceivers could see human infants’ eyes (compared to other babyish features), perceivers judged those human infants to be more vulnerable and felt a stronger need to protect them. Across two experiments, there was no evidence that this was the case. (See Fig 4 for a graphical depiction of the effects that the eye gaze manipulation had, integrated across the 2 experiments.) Intriguingly, Experiment 4 yielded some evidence that puppy dogs—but not human infants—were more likely to elicit such appraisals when they looked directly at perceivers.
